00:00:20.861 --> 00:00:23.110
PROFESSOR: All right, I guess
we can get started here.

00:00:23.110 --> 00:00:24.670
So welcome.

00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:28.290
Today we're going to do
Bayesian updating, which

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:30.490
is to say we're going to
be using Bayes' Theorem

00:00:30.490 --> 00:00:31.560
to learn from data.

00:00:31.560 --> 00:00:33.200
We're going to
update our beliefs

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:36.950
about various hypotheses
based on the data.

00:00:36.950 --> 00:00:40.190
For this week, we're going
to have known priors.

00:00:40.190 --> 00:00:42.570
We're going to know our
belief about the data ahead

00:00:42.570 --> 00:00:43.960
of time for certain.

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:50.480
We'll draw coins out of
drawers or pull things out

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:52.020
of hats, things like that.

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:54.120
Starting next week,
and we discussed

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:56.340
this a little last
time, we'll have

00:00:56.340 --> 00:00:58.050
unknown priors,
which is you'll have

00:00:58.050 --> 00:00:59.380
to be making up those priors.

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:03.050
And we'll teach you
techniques for making it up.

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:10.360
So the first slide is just
XKCD's view of Bayes' Theorem.

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:10.860
Let's go on.

00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:14.645
We want to start with a
clicker question here.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:21.027
So the question is: which
treatment would you choose

00:01:21.027 --> 00:01:22.110
if you needed a treatment?

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:25.870
Treatment 1 cured
100% of the patients.

00:01:25.870 --> 00:01:29.060
Treatment 2 cured
95% in a trial.

00:01:29.060 --> 00:01:31.930
And treatment 3 cured 90%.

00:01:31.930 --> 00:01:34.835
So with this information,
which would you choose?

00:01:39.229 --> 00:01:40.770
AUDIENCE: With only
this information?

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:41.853
PROFESSOR: With only this.

00:01:41.853 --> 00:01:44.610
If this is all I told you.

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:46.020
Which would you choose?

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:48.785
I recognizing that you might
not be too happy with just

00:01:48.785 --> 00:01:52.430
this information, but if this
is their best information, what

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:53.590
would you choose?

00:01:53.590 --> 00:01:57.110
All right, there's some
holdouts for the 95% cure.

00:01:57.110 --> 00:02:00.470
I'm not sure why.

00:02:00.470 --> 00:02:02.740
Really, that 95%
was just, you know,

00:02:02.740 --> 00:02:08.139
they've cured one
person 19 out of 20--

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:11.640
they got them 19 out of 20
well, or however you say that.

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:12.390
Yeah.

00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:16.880
All right, so there's
even a few more holdouts.

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:20.790
All right, what if I gave
you this information?

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:24.590
Treatment 1 cured 3
out of 3 patients.

00:02:24.590 --> 00:02:26.430
That's 100%.

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:28.990
Treatment 2 cured
19 of 20 patients.

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:32.226
That's 95%.

00:02:32.226 --> 00:02:33.600
Or, you have a
standard treatment

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:38.920
which has cured 90,000 out
of 100,000 patients, 90%,

00:02:38.920 --> 00:02:41.120
in clinical practice.

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:42.490
Now which one would you choose?

00:02:49.832 --> 00:02:51.290
PROFESSOR 2: It's
very interesting.

00:02:53.706 --> 00:02:54.747
Yeah, it totally changed.

00:02:54.747 --> 00:02:55.670
PROFESSOR: What's that?

00:02:55.670 --> 00:02:56.580
PROFESSOR 2: It totally shifted.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:58.360
PROFESSOR: It totally
shifted, really?

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.734
PROFESSOR 2: We have a bunch
of very conservative people.

00:03:00.734 --> 00:03:02.400
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:06.800
So the majority would
choose the third choice,

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:09.720
90 out of 100,000.

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:13.554
I think-- well, someone tell
me, what's the intuition there?

00:03:13.554 --> 00:03:15.330
AUDIENCE: Because
it's been more tested.

00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:16.705
PROFESSOR: It's
been more tested.

00:03:16.705 --> 00:03:20.480
3 out of 3 is 100%, but do
you really believe 100%?

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:21.300
Not yet.

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:23.590
Maybe it'll prove out in time.

00:03:23.590 --> 00:03:27.780
19 out of 20 is a little
more, but for most people,

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:31.620
for 79% of you,
that's not enough.

00:03:31.620 --> 00:03:36.110
The 90 out of 100,000
seems like good odds,

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:37.900
and it's well tested.

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:44.130
19 out of 20, if the next person
tested doesn't get better,

00:03:44.130 --> 00:03:46.570
now you back to 90%.

00:03:46.570 --> 00:03:48.650
So that doesn't seem
like quite enough.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:53.372
What if were 95 out
of 100 patients.

00:03:53.372 --> 00:03:54.580
We'll let you click in there.

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:57.020
Change number 2 to 95
out of 100 and let's

00:03:57.020 --> 00:04:00.370
see what people would do.

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:02.780
Oh, you're very
obliging, 95 out of 100--

00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:04.230
PROFESSOR 2: Now
it's about 50-50.

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:05.527
PROFESSOR: About 50-50.

00:04:05.527 --> 00:04:06.735
PROFESSOR 2: Between 2 and 3.

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:10.750
PROFESSOR:
Realistically, of course,

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:11.833
what would you want to do?

00:04:11.833 --> 00:04:14.240
You'd want to do a
little more research

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:17.730
and find out what these trials
were, how good experiments you

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:20.820
thought they were, what
people are thinking about it.

00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:23.290
But with just this data, that's
what people would choose.

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:25.040
And would people would
choose differently.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:27.360
OK.

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:29.810
PROFESSOR 2: Let's see.

00:04:29.810 --> 00:04:33.390
So now I'm going to give
you a toy problem that

00:04:33.390 --> 00:04:35.670
actually mirrors the
same kind of effect we

00:04:35.670 --> 00:04:37.470
saw on the last slide.

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:44.100
So, suppose in this MIT mug,
I have dice of two types,

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:47.710
4-sided and 20-sided.

00:04:47.710 --> 00:04:48.210
All right?

00:04:48.210 --> 00:04:50.760
So I'm going to
reach into the mug.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:53.380
I'm not going to look.

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:55.880
Much.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:58.935
I'm going to randomly
pull out a die.

00:04:58.935 --> 00:04:59.810
I'm going to roll it.

00:05:02.750 --> 00:05:05.200
All right, I got a 1.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:06.450
OK.

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:07.270
I got a 1.

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:13.190
Now, just based on this
information, which type of die

00:05:13.190 --> 00:05:14.480
do you think I randomly chose?

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:17.962
The 4-sided.

00:05:17.962 --> 00:05:20.170
Someone want to give an
explanation of why they think

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:21.728
the 4-sided is more likely?

00:05:21.728 --> 00:05:23.307
AUDIENCE: It's
greater probability.

00:05:23.307 --> 00:05:24.890
PROFESSOR 2: It's
greater probability.

00:05:24.890 --> 00:05:28.180
What's the probability of
getting a 1 on the 4-sided die?

00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:30.230
And what about a 20-sided sided?

00:05:30.230 --> 00:05:30.960
OK.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:35.300
So we see that it would
be more likely to roll a 1

00:05:35.300 --> 00:05:38.180
with a 4-sided die than
with a 20-sided die.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:43.570
So, suppose I tell you that
I really in this cup only

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:46.820
have one die of each type.

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:49.380
So does that change
your analysis

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:50.820
of which die is most likely?

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:52.680
Don't hit forward yet.

00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:54.120
PROFESSOR: I would think of it.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:56.450
My hands are staying.

00:05:56.450 --> 00:06:00.130
PROFESSOR 2: Or do you want to
stick with the same reasoning?

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:00.850
All right.

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:02.683
Let me show you what's
actually in this cup.

00:06:09.002 --> 00:06:09.960
PROFESSOR: Ouch.

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:12.630
PROFESSOR 2: Oh, you
can't see it yet.

00:06:12.630 --> 00:06:15.720
Let's go with the
document camera.

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:22.610
OK, that was actually
what I had in this cup.

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:24.560
Now what?

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:26.510
So does this change at
all of your analysis

00:06:26.510 --> 00:06:29.250
of which die you think I
rolled and got a 1 with?

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:31.082
What type of die, rather?

00:06:31.082 --> 00:06:31.665
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:06:31.665 --> 00:06:32.100
PROFESSOR 2: Yeah?

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:33.810
Now what do you
think is more likely?

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:34.817
4-sided or 20-sided?

00:06:34.817 --> 00:06:36.400
AUDIENCE: How many
20 sided are there?

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:38.441
PROFESSOR 2: I think I
got 20 20-sided die there.

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:49.080
All right, so raise your hand
if you like a 4-sided die.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:51.850
Raise your hand if you
like the 20-sided die.

00:06:51.850 --> 00:06:52.350
Great.

00:06:52.350 --> 00:06:55.230
So that reasoning that
you're doing intuitively

00:06:55.230 --> 00:06:57.560
is something that we want
to formalize this week

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:59.930
and next week using
Bayes' Theorem

00:06:59.930 --> 00:07:02.460
to do these calculations
in a systematic way,

00:07:02.460 --> 00:07:06.380
to evaluate hypotheses
based on data.

00:07:06.380 --> 00:07:10.230
And these numbers,
for example, how many

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:12.370
die I had of one
type versus another,

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:14.980
we can encode that information
in what's called a prior,

00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:16.285
and we'll come to that today.

00:07:16.285 --> 00:07:18.410
And you should've seen, in
your reading, this idea.

00:07:22.612 --> 00:07:24.820
PROFESSOR: OK so I'm going
to work through an example

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:25.420
to start with.

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:31.090
We have 3 types of coins:
type A, B, and C. However

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:34.210
it happens, the probability
of getting heads with type A

00:07:34.210 --> 00:07:35.040
is 0.5.

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:36.130
That's a fair coin.

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:40.820
The probability of getting
heads with type B is 0.6,

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:44.000
and of type C is 0.9.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.210
And here's a box that
contains two of the fair coins

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:49.460
and one of each of the other.

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:54.070
So two of type A, one of
type B, and one of type C.

00:07:54.070 --> 00:07:56.490
Suppose I pick one at
random and I get heads.

00:07:56.490 --> 00:08:00.160
So this is like John picking a
die at random, and getting a 1.

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:02.900
I get heads.

00:08:02.900 --> 00:08:04.900
Here's the question:
before I flipped it,

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:08.930
I have a prior belief
in the probability

00:08:08.930 --> 00:08:11.290
that the coin was
of each type based

00:08:11.290 --> 00:08:13.610
on the number in my drawer.

00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:17.390
After flipping it,
my belief changes.

00:08:17.390 --> 00:08:22.180
The probability will change
based on the data I get.

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:24.160
And so a question you
could ask: what was

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:27.590
learned by flipping the coin?

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:31.150
What we want to teach you to
do to answer these questions,

00:08:31.150 --> 00:08:33.270
we have a nice
way of summarizing

00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:36.280
all of that once in a table.

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:44.090
So here the notation, we
have this nice scripty H--

00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:44.775
that's no good.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:49.496
H is our hypothesis.

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:58.740
That is, you're of
type A or B or C.

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:06.690
We're going to make a conjecture
on what we think the coin was.

00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:11.330
Before we do anything,
we have a prior.

00:09:11.330 --> 00:09:13.910
So what's the
probability of-- how

00:09:13.910 --> 00:09:17.240
did I label this-- that
the coin was of type A?

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:24.045
Where all you know is I
pulled it out of the drawer.

00:09:24.045 --> 00:09:26.385
So what's the probability
it's of type A.

00:09:26.385 --> 00:09:28.135
PROFESSOR 2: Let me
go back and remind you

00:09:28.135 --> 00:09:31.570
what the drawer looks like.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:33.850
What is it?

00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:35.040
PROFESSOR: 0.5.

00:09:35.040 --> 00:09:36.590
0.5, or I'll write it like this.

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:39.390
2 out of 4, which is 0.5.

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:41.240
And what's the
probability-- I'll

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:52.180
shorten this-- for just
type B. Yeah, 1/4 or 0.25.

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:58.940
The probability that we're
of type C is 1/4 or 0.25.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:01.565
This was one of our
simpler counting problems.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:06.380
In the table, you can
see that's encoded

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:09.860
in the line in the
column marked prior.

00:10:09.860 --> 00:10:13.150
Before we take any data,
this is what we'd say.

00:10:13.150 --> 00:10:16.221
This is the sort of
odds we'd give if we

00:10:16.221 --> 00:10:18.440
were going to bet on this.

00:10:18.440 --> 00:10:19.770
But now we have some data.

00:10:22.790 --> 00:10:28.000
So once we have data we
can get the likelihood.

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:34.540
The likelihood is
the probability

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:37.556
of seeing the data
given a hypothesis.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:43.590
I won't write this out, I'll
just point at the slide.

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:46.749
John has a-- you were going
to make your mouse bigger.

00:10:46.749 --> 00:10:47.540
PROFESSOR 2: I was.

00:10:47.540 --> 00:10:48.123
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:53.180
So the likelihood
column-- we use

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:56.210
this term when we are talking
about maximum likelihood--

00:10:56.210 --> 00:11:00.240
is the probability of the
data given the hypothesis.

00:11:00.240 --> 00:11:06.010
And this is typically easy,
or often easy, to figure out.

00:11:06.010 --> 00:11:07.800
What's the probability
of seeing heads--

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:12.850
our data was I flipped a heads--
if my coin is a 0.5 probability

00:11:12.850 --> 00:11:13.350
coin.

00:11:17.560 --> 00:11:25.550
So the probability of seeing
heads given a type A coin

00:11:25.550 --> 00:11:26.170
is what?

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:28.660
Somebody.

00:11:28.660 --> 00:11:30.644
It's 0.5.

00:11:30.644 --> 00:11:32.310
This is particularly
easy because that's

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:33.018
what we told you.

00:11:33.018 --> 00:11:38.480
The probability of heads
with a type A coin is 0.5.

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:47.160
What about for B
and C. 0.6 and 0.9.

00:11:47.160 --> 00:11:52.650
So there right here is the
likelihood column in the table.

00:11:52.650 --> 00:11:56.350
Now, how do we
get the posterior?

00:11:56.350 --> 00:12:02.390
Bayes' Theorem says
the probability of H

00:12:02.390 --> 00:12:04.760
given D, which is what I want.

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:06.630
I want to know,
given this data, what

00:12:06.630 --> 00:12:08.670
do I believe the coin to be?

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:11.060
What's its probability?

00:12:11.060 --> 00:12:17.610
Is the probability of D given
H times the probability of H

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:20.840
all over the probability of D.

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:24.230
Well, notice this
numerator right here.

00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:28.430
That's just our likelihood
times our hypothesis,

00:12:28.430 --> 00:12:32.280
our prior belief
in our hypothesis.

00:12:32.280 --> 00:12:36.390
And so what do we get when
I multiply the prior column

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:37.860
by the likelihood column?

00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:39.720
I get this column in red.

00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:41.910
And I'll call that the
unnormalized posterior.

00:12:41.910 --> 00:12:42.880
Why unnormalized?

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.320
Because it doesn't sum to 1.

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:48.160
How do I get it to sum to 1?

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:52.070
There I have to divide by
the probability of the data.

00:12:52.070 --> 00:12:54.050
And how do I get the
probability of the data?

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:03.942
That's called the-- I
see someone mouthing it.

00:13:03.942 --> 00:13:05.150
The Law of Total Probability.

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:10.540
And the Law of Total
Probability says

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:14.330
you multiply, for
each hypothesis,

00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:19.340
this value times this
value and add them up.

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:25.820
Which is in fact just the
sum of the red column.

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:28.340
So there I've written it: 0.625.

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:29.750
And now, how do I normalize?

00:13:29.750 --> 00:13:34.160
I just divide all my values
in my unnormalized column

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:37.430
by that normalizing
factor, 0.625,

00:13:37.430 --> 00:13:40.640
and I get these, what
I call the posterior.

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:47.117
Let's say-- well, now
let's analyze this.

00:13:47.117 --> 00:13:48.200
So now what's your belief?

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:52.130
Which coin is the
most likely coin?

00:13:52.130 --> 00:13:53.400
After seeing this data.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:59.870
Still A. But what's
happened to the probability

00:13:59.870 --> 00:14:02.770
from our prior probability?

00:14:02.770 --> 00:14:03.370
It's dropped.

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:06.041
Which one has
gained probability.

00:14:06.041 --> 00:14:06.540
AUDIENCE: C.

00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:07.998
PROFESSOR: C. Does
that make sense?

00:14:07.998 --> 00:14:14.440
If I flip a heads, which coin is
the most likely to flip heads?

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:15.930
C. So I've shifted it.

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:19.120
