00:26:57.950 --> 00:26:59.300
die.

00:26:59.300 --> 00:26:59.890
0.

00:26:59.890 --> 00:27:00.390
Right?

00:27:00.390 --> 00:27:01.150
It's impossible.

00:27:01.150 --> 00:27:04.780
Similarly 4, 6, 8 and 12 sides.

00:27:04.780 --> 00:27:07.440
But given that I had
the 20-sided die,

00:27:07.440 --> 00:27:10.850
there would be a 1/20
probability of rolling a 13.

00:27:10.850 --> 00:27:12.306
That's the likelihood column.

00:27:12.306 --> 00:27:13.280
All right.

00:27:13.280 --> 00:27:16.140
The next column, what we called
the unnormalized posterior, we

00:27:16.140 --> 00:27:19.840
multiply, everything is 0,
and then we get 1 out of 100

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:25.140
as the product for
the 20-sided die.

00:27:25.140 --> 00:27:29.100
If we sum this up by the
Law of Total Probability,

00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:31.201
we get the probability
of the data.

00:27:31.201 --> 00:27:32.950
Now, a student asked,
what does that mean?

00:27:32.950 --> 00:27:34.770
We don't know which die it was?

00:27:34.770 --> 00:27:37.850
In this case, what
it means is that it's

00:27:37.850 --> 00:27:42.630
reasonable to ask the question,
well, if someone reaches in,

00:27:42.630 --> 00:27:45.780
grabs 1 of these 5 dice
randomly and rolls it

00:27:45.780 --> 00:27:48.070
and gets-- I mean,
what's the probability

00:27:48.070 --> 00:27:50.440
that the result would be a 13.

00:27:50.440 --> 00:27:50.980
Right?

00:27:50.980 --> 00:27:53.270
That's a reasonable question.

00:27:53.270 --> 00:27:56.790
And in this case, it's not so
hard to analyze that directly,

00:27:56.790 --> 00:27:58.870
because the only way
that could happen

00:27:58.870 --> 00:28:02.780
is if they picked the 20-sided
die and then rolled a 13.

00:28:02.780 --> 00:28:06.370
Well, given that they
picked the 20-sided die.

00:28:06.370 --> 00:28:09.440
Well, there's a 1/5 chance
they picked the 20-sided die,

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:13.010
and then a 1/20 chance they
roll of 13 given that they

00:28:13.010 --> 00:28:15.080
picked the 20-sided die.

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:20.880
So the probability of rolling
a 13 overall is 1 in 100.

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:23.369
The probability of the data.

00:28:23.369 --> 00:28:25.160
PROFESSOR: John, let
me just say one thing.

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:27.035
The way we would have
done this before is you

00:28:27.035 --> 00:28:28.990
would have made a tree.

00:28:28.990 --> 00:28:30.690
The top branch of
the tree would have

00:28:30.690 --> 00:28:33.440
gone to the 5 types of die,
and then each of those die

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:35.570
would have gone to
all the possibilities.

00:28:35.570 --> 00:28:39.340
And the only branch
that leads to a 13

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:42.874
is down to the 20-sided die
and then down to the 13.

00:28:42.874 --> 00:28:44.540
PROFESSOR 2: Notice
also that this would

00:28:44.540 --> 00:28:47.100
be a very big tree, right?

00:28:47.100 --> 00:28:50.700
You have 5 branches, and
then this would have 4 and 6,

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:53.480
and 8, and 12, and
20 coming off of it.

00:28:53.480 --> 00:28:54.630
Finally we normalize.

00:28:54.630 --> 00:28:57.330
Using Bayes Rule, this gives
us a posterior probability mass

00:28:57.330 --> 00:28:57.890
function.

00:28:57.890 --> 00:29:01.370
It's 0 for everything but
the 20-sided hypothesis.

00:29:01.370 --> 00:29:06.090
Therefore, we get 100%
belief, 100% probability,

00:29:06.090 --> 00:29:09.930
given that we rolled a 13,
that it was the 20-sided die.

00:29:09.930 --> 00:29:12.870
Now of course you all
knew that immediately.

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:15.140
If you roll a 13, it has
to be the 20-sided die.

00:29:15.140 --> 00:29:17.540
So let's look at a more
interesting one that you did,

00:29:17.540 --> 00:29:18.050
the 5.

00:29:18.050 --> 00:29:18.950
So what changes?

00:29:18.950 --> 00:29:21.270
That's the big question.

00:29:21.270 --> 00:29:27.494
The only thing that
changes is the likelihood.

00:29:27.494 --> 00:29:28.910
I mean, granted,
the rest changes.

00:29:28.910 --> 00:29:30.540
But everything in
these two columns

00:29:30.540 --> 00:29:32.250
are computed from the first two.

00:29:32.250 --> 00:29:37.080
The prior stays the same, but
the likelihood function changes

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:38.860
because we have different data.

00:29:38.860 --> 00:29:40.890
In this case, if we
roll a 5, we can't

00:29:40.890 --> 00:29:42.980
get that on the 4-sided die.

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:45.930
We have a 1/6 chance on the
6-sided, 1/8 on the 8-sided,

00:29:45.930 --> 00:29:48.970
1/12 on the 12-sided and
1/20 on the 20-sided.

00:29:48.970 --> 00:29:52.270
Multiply those columns, get
the unnormalized probability,

00:29:52.270 --> 00:29:54.860
or the unnormalized posterior.

00:29:54.860 --> 00:29:58.040
That sums to the
probability of getting a 5.

00:29:58.040 --> 00:30:01.160
When you divide by it, it
normalizes the posterior,

00:30:01.160 --> 00:30:02.990
and what do we see?

00:30:02.990 --> 00:30:07.260
Well, of course you couldn't
have used the 4-sided die,

00:30:07.260 --> 00:30:11.500
and of the remaining the most
likely, the most probable,

00:30:11.500 --> 00:30:15.560
given the data, is
the 6-sided die.

00:30:15.560 --> 00:30:17.310
It has a probability,
that hypothesis

00:30:17.310 --> 00:30:21.470
has a probability of about 40%,
compared to the 20-sided die,

00:30:21.470 --> 00:30:24.020
which is only about 12%.

00:30:24.020 --> 00:30:25.270
OK.

00:30:25.270 --> 00:30:27.450
Last one.

00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:28.620
So this is the same deal.

00:30:28.620 --> 00:30:31.530
Again, the likelihood
function changes.

00:30:31.530 --> 00:30:32.890
The prior's the same.

00:30:32.890 --> 00:30:34.230
We go through the table.

00:30:34.230 --> 00:30:36.450
The only two possibilities
are the 12 and 20-sided,

00:30:36.450 --> 00:30:38.850
and the 12-sided, given
that you rolled a 9,

00:30:38.850 --> 00:30:42.360
is about twice as likely
as the 20-sided, which

00:30:42.360 --> 00:30:45.680
should fit with your intuition.

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:46.530
OK.

00:30:46.530 --> 00:30:50.150
So next, we want you to
not erase, but go back

00:30:50.150 --> 00:30:51.810
to the boards
you've already made,

00:30:51.810 --> 00:30:54.370
and we're going to explore a
little bit the idea of repeated

00:30:54.370 --> 00:30:55.070
trials.

00:30:55.070 --> 00:30:55.570
Right?

00:30:55.570 --> 00:30:58.070
Often if you're collecting
data, you don't just

00:30:58.070 --> 00:31:00.120
collect one data
point, you collect

00:31:00.120 --> 00:31:02.860
a series of data points,
maybe a series of patients

00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:03.950
in a clinical trial.

00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:05.520
You have data coming in, right?

00:31:05.520 --> 00:31:06.730
And you can update.

00:31:06.730 --> 00:31:09.110
You can update each
time you get more data.

00:31:09.110 --> 00:31:12.585
And when you do this, your
prior becomes a posterior

00:31:12.585 --> 00:31:13.960
in the first
update, and then you

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:17.110
use that posterior as the
prior for the next update.

00:31:17.110 --> 00:31:21.680
Your beliefs are being
updated as more data comes in.

00:31:21.680 --> 00:31:24.390
If you think about it, like when
you walk outside this course,

00:31:24.390 --> 00:31:26.694
if you're like me
you'll sort of suddenly

00:31:26.694 --> 00:31:28.610
realize you're doing
this process all the time

00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:30.500
in your life, and you'll start
approaching problems this way.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:31.874
And if you really
like me, you'll

00:31:31.874 --> 00:31:34.530
change your religion on
Facebook to Bayesian.

00:31:34.530 --> 00:31:37.110
But you don't have
to be that extreme.

00:31:37.110 --> 00:31:39.180
So great.

00:31:39.180 --> 00:31:42.970
So here what we want you to do
is pretend that I roll the die

00:31:42.970 --> 00:31:43.860
and then got a 5.

