No, because in order to use
the Law of Total Probability,

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:10.860
you have to multiply
your likelihood

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:12.730
by genuine probabilities.

00:38:12.730 --> 00:38:15.407
And the unnormalized posterior
is not a genuine probability.

00:38:15.407 --> 00:38:17.240
AUDIENCE: But if you
use the normalized one.

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:18.990
PROFESSOR: If you used
the normalized one,

00:38:18.990 --> 00:38:24.210
then it would be-- that would be
the total probability of that.

00:38:24.210 --> 00:38:25.235
That's exactly right.

00:38:25.235 --> 00:38:26.610
AUDIENCE: But, in
this case, it's

00:38:26.610 --> 00:38:28.050
this that's the total
probability, right?

00:38:28.050 --> 00:38:28.716
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:38:28.716 --> 00:38:31.440
This is now your
posterior probability.

00:38:31.440 --> 00:38:32.690
These are now the probability.

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:34.110
So, make a distinction.

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:36.970
The total probability
is about the data,

00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:42.249
and these probabilities here
are about the hypotheses.

00:38:42.249 --> 00:38:45.182
AUDIENCE: Sort of like the fit
of the hypothesis to the data.

00:38:45.182 --> 00:38:46.640
PROFESSOR: You
could think of that.

00:38:46.640 --> 00:38:47.890
They're genuine probabilities.

00:38:47.890 --> 00:38:52.700
This is the probability that
you chose the 12-sided die given

00:38:52.700 --> 00:38:53.200
the data.

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:59.410
That is, if I did this a
million times and every time,

00:38:59.410 --> 00:39:02.360
I only looked at the times
I rolled a 9 and then the 5,

00:39:02.360 --> 00:39:05.160
you would find this
fraction of those times

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:07.460
would be-- it
would be a 12-sided

00:39:07.460 --> 00:39:09.060
and this fraction
would be a 20-sided.

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:12.320
So, I forget what the
numbers were, like 3 to 1.

00:39:12.320 --> 00:39:12.920
Yeah.

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:13.942
Makes sense?

00:39:13.942 --> 00:39:15.270
Excellent.

00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:19.010
AUDIENCE: So we multiply
them together, but then--

00:39:19.010 --> 00:39:21.170
PROFESSOR 2: You get the
same exact answer, right?

00:39:21.170 --> 00:39:23.332
AUDIENCE: So we get
these, this answer.

00:39:23.332 --> 00:39:25.790
AUDIENCE 2: That's right,
so it's unnormalized.

00:39:25.790 --> 00:39:26.520
PROFESSOR: And
then you normalize

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:27.770
it and you get this, right.

00:39:27.770 --> 00:39:31.015
AUDIENCE: There's no way
to normalize it without--

00:39:31.015 --> 00:39:33.390
PROFESSOR 2: All right, let's
come back together and take

00:39:33.390 --> 00:39:35.070
a look at what happened here.

00:39:38.470 --> 00:39:39.910
I saw some aha moments.

00:39:39.910 --> 00:39:40.590
That was great.

00:39:43.410 --> 00:39:45.160
Some people cited The
Commutative Property

00:39:45.160 --> 00:39:46.040
of Multiplication.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:47.040
That made me very happy.

00:39:49.510 --> 00:39:52.100
So, what do we do?

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:54.175
So when we do the
9 and then the 5,

00:39:54.175 --> 00:39:56.300
it looks just like what I
did with the 5 and the 9,

00:39:56.300 --> 00:39:59.240
except the likelihood
columns are flipped.

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:04.490
So we have our prior,
the likelihood for the 9

00:40:04.490 --> 00:40:07.050
gives us this column.

00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:10.550
The product gives us an,
first, unnormalized posterior.

00:40:10.550 --> 00:40:14.540
Then we do the likelihood
for rolling a 5.

00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:17.000
The product of the
unnormalized posterior

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:18.750
and the second
likelihood gives us

00:40:18.750 --> 00:40:22.410
our final unnormalized
posterior.

00:40:22.410 --> 00:40:25.550
And notice the sum is still
exactly what it was before,

00:40:25.550 --> 00:40:27.910
0.019.

00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:30.940
When we normalize, we get
exactly the same answer

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:31.810
that we had before.

00:40:31.810 --> 00:40:34.720
Now, if you contrast
this with the table

00:40:34.720 --> 00:40:36.680
we looked at when we
did the 5 and then

00:40:36.680 --> 00:40:41.940
the 9, what changed is these
two columns were flipped around.

00:40:41.940 --> 00:40:44.210
And so I suppose this
column was different

00:40:44.210 --> 00:40:45.960
and this column was
different as a result.

00:40:45.960 --> 00:40:50.740
And then the final result,
however, was exactly the same.

00:40:50.740 --> 00:40:53.674
Now, what if we do
them both at once?

00:40:53.674 --> 00:40:54.590
What should that mean?

00:40:57.340 --> 00:40:59.500
If we do them both
at once, then,

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:02.220
well we start from the
same uniform prior,

00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:05.780
and our likelihood-- now,
we should think of the data

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:09.700
as both rolls, the 5 and the 9.

00:41:09.700 --> 00:41:10.790
OK.

00:41:10.790 --> 00:41:15.100
Now what's important here
is that if we condition

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:16.400
on a given hypothesis.

00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:18.970
For example, if we
condition on the hypothesis

00:41:18.970 --> 00:41:22.980
that it's a 12-sided
die, then the first roll

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:27.130
and the second roll are
independent events, right?

00:41:27.130 --> 00:41:31.260
It means that we can figure
out the probability of a 5

00:41:31.260 --> 00:41:33.430
and then a 9 on
the 12-sided die.

00:41:33.430 --> 00:41:35.610
It's just the product
of the probability

00:41:35.610 --> 00:41:38.820
of a 5 and a 12-sided die
and the probability of a 9

00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:40.140
on a 12-sided die.

00:41:40.140 --> 00:41:42.270
That's why we're justified
in taking the product.

00:41:42.270 --> 00:41:45.890
If we condition on the die
that it is, on the hypothesis,

00:41:45.890 --> 00:41:50.280
12-sided, then the rolls are
all independent of each other.

00:41:50.280 --> 00:41:55.070
In particular, we get 1/12
times 1/12 for rolling a 5

00:41:55.070 --> 00:41:56.080
and then rolling a 9.

00:41:56.080 --> 00:41:58.820
And for the 20-sided die,
we get 1/20 times 1/20.

00:42:01.750 --> 00:42:05.260
So now in one step, we update.

00:42:05.260 --> 00:42:12.100
Same exact sum, we
normalize, same exact answer.

00:42:12.100 --> 00:42:16.300
And I mentioned that some
groups, maybe when slightly

00:42:16.300 --> 00:42:21.290
prompted by me, said oh,
multiplication is commutative.

00:42:21.290 --> 00:42:22.020
Right?

00:42:22.020 --> 00:42:24.390
That's all that's going on here.

00:42:24.390 --> 00:42:26.260
In the end, all
we're doing is taking

00:42:26.260 --> 00:42:29.300
our prior, the first likelihood
column, the second likelihood

00:42:29.300 --> 00:42:31.660
column, multiplying them
together and then normalizing

00:42:31.660 --> 00:42:32.180
it.

00:42:32.180 --> 00:42:33.182
Right?

00:42:33.182 --> 00:42:35.390
It doesn't matter what order
those likelihood columns

00:42:35.390 --> 00:42:35.680
are in.

00:42:35.680 --> 00:42:37.263
It doesn't matter
if we think of the 5

00:42:37.263 --> 00:42:39.310
and then the 9, the 9
and the 5, or the 5 and 9

00:42:39.310 --> 00:42:41.900
multiplied together to make
their own likelihood column.

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:44.240
You get the same exact
unnormalized result no matter

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:45.870
what.

00:42:45.870 --> 00:42:46.580
OK.

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:50.380
So this is all there is
to why it doesn't matter

00:42:50.380 --> 00:42:53.900
what order you update
the data in sequentially,

00:42:53.900 --> 00:42:56.110
it just matters
what the data is.

00:42:56.110 --> 00:42:57.960
Now I also had a question.

00:42:57.960 --> 00:43:00.880
Why, if you could
do it all once,

00:43:00.880 --> 00:43:04.740
would you even bother with
doing it once and then

00:43:04.740 --> 00:43:06.280
doing it again?

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:08.180
It's a very good question.

00:43:08.180 --> 00:43:11.079
Does anyone want to
suggest a reason?

00:43:11.079 --> 00:43:12.745
Maybe other than the
group that I talked

00:43:12.745 --> 00:43:16.594
to specifically about it Yeah.

00:43:16.594 --> 00:43:18.010
AUDIENCE: Well,
I'm just thinking,

00:43:18.010 --> 00:43:20.146
as you're saying, if you
have ongoing patients

00:43:20.146 --> 00:43:22.450
and you have to like
continuously update,

00:43:22.450 --> 00:43:25.866
then the first
data set may be all

00:43:25.866 --> 00:43:27.616
that you have at that
moment, but then you

00:43:27.616 --> 00:43:29.004
have to keeping adding on to it.

00:43:29.004 --> 00:43:30.420
PROFESSOR 2: That's
exactly right.

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:31.370
That's exactly right.

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:36.280
So, in life and in
clinical trials,

00:43:36.280 --> 00:43:38.680
you don't get all the
data necessarily at once.

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:42.579
It sort of comes
in continuously.

00:43:42.579 --> 00:43:44.370
When I wake up in the
morning, I don't know

00:43:44.370 --> 00:43:46.900
what temperature it is outside.

00:43:46.900 --> 00:43:49.004
I have a prior, based
on what temperature

00:43:49.004 --> 00:43:50.670
it was yesterday at
about the same time,

00:43:50.670 --> 00:43:52.227
like I have a memory of that.

00:43:52.227 --> 00:43:53.810
So it gives me some
prior distribution

00:43:53.810 --> 00:43:55.140
on the temperature.

00:43:55.140 --> 00:43:57.640
OK, that might be a continuous
one, like maybe a bell curve.

00:43:57.640 --> 00:44:00.441
We're going to get to that next
week, these continuous updating

00:44:00.441 --> 00:44:00.940
problems.

00:44:00.940 --> 00:44:02.110
OK.

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:03.590
And then, when I
get out of bed, I

00:44:03.590 --> 00:44:06.940
see that the window is
covered in condensation.

00:44:06.940 --> 00:44:08.310
That's some data.

00:44:08.310 --> 00:44:09.440
I can update my beliefs.

00:44:09.440 --> 00:44:12.790
Probably means
it's kind of cold.

00:44:12.790 --> 00:44:13.910
Great.

00:44:13.910 --> 00:44:16.640
Then I can open the
window to let the cat out,

00:44:16.640 --> 00:44:18.870
and a burst of freezing
cold air comes in,

00:44:18.870 --> 00:44:21.328
like it did this morning--
well, actually not this morning.

00:44:21.328 --> 00:44:22.960
This morning was great.

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:25.700
Yesterday it was cold.

00:44:25.700 --> 00:44:28.841
And again, now I have more
data and I update my beliefs.

00:44:28.841 --> 00:44:29.340
All right.

00:44:29.340 --> 00:44:30.715
You can go through
life this way.

00:44:30.715 --> 00:44:32.810
It'll give you a headache,
but you can do it.

00:44:32.810 --> 00:44:36.070
Now, with clinical trials,
the same thing can happen.

00:44:36.070 --> 00:44:37.320
Maybe you do a pilot study.

00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:44.930
Maybe you have some belief
that eating almonds causes

00:44:44.930 --> 00:44:48.220
something, stomach cramps.

00:44:48.220 --> 00:44:48.970
Great.

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:50.940
And maybe it's just for you.

00:44:50.940 --> 00:44:52.582
But you want to do
a study about that.

00:44:52.582 --> 00:44:55.040
So maybe you know for yourself
that eating almonds give you

00:44:55.040 --> 00:44:56.500
stomach cramps.

00:44:56.500 --> 00:44:58.550
You're at the Harvard
School of Public Health

00:44:58.550 --> 00:45:00.820
and you really want to
investigate this further,

00:45:00.820 --> 00:45:03.130
so you gather a few
willing subjects,

00:45:03.130 --> 00:45:05.780
you feed them some almonds, you
see if they get stomach cramps,

00:45:05.780 --> 00:45:07.080
how many of them.

00:45:07.080 --> 00:45:09.800
And maybe your prior
ahead was you just kind of

00:45:09.800 --> 00:45:12.024
felt like you had this
really strong belief that

00:45:12.024 --> 00:45:13.690
almonds cause stomach
cramps, because it

00:45:13.690 --> 00:45:14.670
does for you and you
really haven't even

00:45:14.670 --> 00:45:15.650
asked a lot of other people.

00:45:15.650 --> 00:45:17.483
So you might have a lot
of prior probability

00:45:17.483 --> 00:45:19.630
on that hypothesis being true.

00:45:19.630 --> 00:45:21.060
Once you collect
a few more people

00:45:21.060 --> 00:45:22.930
and maybe you ask your
friends, maybe you

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:25.054
find that most of them
don't have the same problem.

00:45:25.054 --> 00:45:27.920
Suddenly your posterior
belief changes

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:30.880
and now you're not quite so
convinced that it's true.

00:45:30.880 --> 00:45:32.470
And then, if you're
really ambitious

00:45:32.470 --> 00:45:35.010
and you have a lot of
grant money from the NIH,

00:45:35.010 --> 00:45:36.880
you recruit 1,000
people and you do

00:45:36.880 --> 00:45:39.020
a randomized controlled
trial with placebo

00:45:39.020 --> 00:45:43.760
and you find out that
exactly 10% of the folks

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:46.310
complain about the stomach
cramps with almonds.

00:45:46.310 --> 00:45:48.069
Maybe 10% on placebo
also, so you're

00:45:48.069 --> 00:45:49.360
not quite sure what's going on.

00:45:49.360 --> 00:45:51.528
But the point is,
you're getting data

00:45:51.528 --> 00:45:52.736
a little more, a little more.

00:45:52.736 --> 00:45:57.410
And you can keep incorporating
it, updating your beliefs.

00:45:57.410 --> 00:45:58.810
So that's the principle.

00:45:58.810 --> 00:46:00.660
One last thing
I'll point out is,

00:46:00.660 --> 00:46:02.640
what if you have a
prior belief that

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:07.210
is so strong, so you are
so sure, for example,

00:46:07.210 --> 00:46:10.025
that almonds don't
cause stomach pain,

00:46:10.025 --> 00:46:12.400
because it doesn't for you
and you're just sure that that

00:46:12.400 --> 00:46:14.136
would be ridiculous, right?

00:46:14.136 --> 00:46:15.885
So you've put your
prior probability at 0.

00:46:18.557 --> 00:46:20.640
How much evidence will it
take, how much data will

00:46:20.640 --> 00:46:22.680
take for you to be convinced?

00:46:25.280 --> 00:46:26.150
Infinite.

00:46:26.150 --> 00:46:30.480
No amount of data is going
to convince you otherwise.

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:33.580
This is why whenever you do
this kind of Bayesian Updating,

00:46:33.580 --> 00:46:37.620
it's generally best to leave
a little bit of possibility

00:46:37.620 --> 00:46:39.580
for Santa Claus, OK.

00:46:39.580 --> 00:46:41.300
Like a little bit.

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:46.040
Just so that, should a fat
white man come down your chimney

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:48.170
and deliver the
presents one year,

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:52.300
you have a
possibility to adjust.

00:46:52.300 --> 00:46:55.340
So those are some
things to keep in mind.

00:46:55.340 --> 00:46:57.770
I think we've got one
more board question

00:46:57.770 --> 00:46:59.860
that Jerry's going to lead.

00:46:59.860 --> 00:47:05.080
PROFESSOR: Right, so it's
nice to get probabilities

00:47:05.080 --> 00:47:08.110
for hypotheses, but one
thing you also want to do

00:47:08.110 --> 00:47:10.850
is predict what's
going to come next.

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:15.320
And so that's what we call
probabilistic prediction.

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:19.870
If I pick one of the John's 5
die, and I'm about to roll it,

00:47:19.870 --> 00:47:23.200
you could tell me using the
Law of Total Probability

00:47:23.200 --> 00:47:27.740
the probability that I get a 5.

00:47:27.740 --> 00:47:30.530
And we've done that, we
did that in the first unit

00:47:30.530 --> 00:47:32.890
on probability in this class.

00:47:32.890 --> 00:47:37.960
But suppose he rolls a 5 first.

00:47:37.960 --> 00:47:41.650
Now I can update my
probabilities for which

00:47:41.650 --> 00:47:43.200
die it is, which
is going to update

00:47:43.200 --> 00:47:48.200
my estimation of the
probability of rolling, say a 4

00:47:48.200 --> 00:47:49.779
on the next roll.

00:47:49.779 --> 00:47:51.820
This is what we'll call
probabilistic prediction.

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:54.240
We can predict what's
going to happen next,

00:47:54.240 --> 00:47:59.104
at least with probabilities,
based on the data

00:47:59.104 --> 00:47:59.770
that we've seen.

00:47:59.770 --> 00:48:03.660
We update our predictions
based on that.

00:48:03.660 --> 00:48:05.220
So here's a set up.

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:06.510
D_1 is the first roll.

00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:07.380
D_2 is the second.

00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:12.202
I'll do this example.

00:48:12.202 --> 00:48:13.410
Oh no, this a board question.

00:48:13.410 --> 00:48:15.280
You're going to do this.

00:48:15.280 --> 00:48:16.430
You're on your own here.

00:48:16.430 --> 00:48:18.860
So first, you
don't know anything

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:23.510
about the die except that 1
of the 5 was chosen at random.

00:48:23.510 --> 00:48:27.320
What's the probability that
the first roll will be a 5?

00:48:27.320 --> 00:48:31.690
Now you've rolled that once,
and you're going to roll again.

00:48:31.690 --> 00:48:34.030
And you can ask, well
now I've seen some data.

00:48:34.030 --> 00:48:38.350
I have some information
about which die was chosen.

00:48:38.350 --> 00:48:41.810
What's the probability that
I'll see a 4 on the next die.

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:45.280
So that's your job to find
that for this problem.

00:48:52.368 --> 00:48:54.826
PROFESSOR 2: Cool, all right,
so this is your first answer?

00:48:54.826 --> 00:48:55.492
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:48:55.492 --> 00:48:58.810
And then, now we're
just multiplying across.

00:48:58.810 --> 00:49:01.798
You get 0.

00:49:01.798 --> 00:49:14.248
1 over 180, 1 over 320,
1 over 740, [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:14.248 --> 00:49:19.726
And then add those up.

00:49:19.726 --> 00:49:22.150
PROFESSOR 2: Yeah, get
out your calculator.

00:49:22.150 --> 00:49:23.775
What are you dividing
by to normalize?

00:49:23.775 --> 00:49:25.397
AUDIENCE: Is this--
I don't know.

00:49:25.397 --> 00:49:26.480
PROFESSOR 2: That's right.

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:31.190
So this is, when you add these
up, exactly the probability

00:49:31.190 --> 00:49:32.249
of the 5, right?

00:49:32.249 --> 00:49:34.040
So now, if you want to
repeat this process,

00:49:34.040 --> 00:49:36.920
you need to use your
normalized posterior instead

00:49:36.920 --> 00:49:37.920
of the original prior.

00:49:37.920 --> 00:49:38.826
AUDIENCE: That's what we were--

00:49:38.826 --> 00:49:39.732
PROFESSOR 2: Yeah.

00:49:39.732 --> 00:49:41.550
Great.

00:49:41.550 --> 00:49:43.100
Now, you just need
to do division.

00:49:43.100 --> 00:49:46.140
That I can't help you with.

00:49:46.140 --> 00:49:48.780
Calculator.

00:49:48.780 --> 00:49:50.226
Division skills, either way.

00:49:58.207 --> 00:49:59.040
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:50:13.597 --> 00:50:15.555
PROFESSOR 2: Now, is this
the probability of 4,

00:50:15.555 --> 00:50:18.184
or the probability of 4 given 5?

00:50:18.184 --> 00:50:18.725
That's right.

00:50:21.350 --> 00:50:25.700
So tell me what you
did to get these.

00:50:25.700 --> 00:50:28.676
AUDIENCE: So this
column [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:28.676 --> 00:50:31.156
which we calculated
for, and then you

